entry.title: Has Khalifa Haftar's campaign in Libya failed? I Inside Story

media:group.media:title: Has Khalifa Haftar's campaign in Libya failed? I Inside Story
media:group.media:description:
Khalifa Haftar's ambitions in Libya are unravelling quickly. The warlord launched an offensive 14 months ago to capture the capital Tripoli from the UN-recognised Government of National Accord, or GNA. Its forces say they've regained full control of Tripoli, and pushed Haftar's fighters from Tarhouna, their last stronghold in western Libya. That follows weeks of similar defeats and losses of territory along the coast. Momentum began to shift in January when Turkey started sending troops and drones to support the GNA. How has this changing the course of the war? And are Khalifa Haftar's days numbered?
Presenter: Bernard Smith
Guests:
Bilgehan Ozturk - Researcher at SETA Foundation, a think-tank
Mansour El Kikhia - Professor of Politics at the University of Texas in San Antonio
William Lawrence - Senior Adjunct Professorial Lecturer at the American University's School of International Service

entry.title: Brexit back on agenda despite coronavirus pandemic

media:group.media:title: Brexit back on agenda despite coronavirus pandemic
media:group.media:description:
In the United Kingdom, Brexit is back on the agenda, and things are not going well. A week of talks between British and European officials has ended in a deadlock and recriminations on both sides. With time running out, the UK insists it will still finally say goodbye with or without a trade deal by the end of the year and with or without a pandemic to deal with. Al Jazeera's Laurence Lee reports from England.

entry.title: Mexico police set on fire during protests against fatal beating

media:group.media:title: Mexico police set on fire during protests against fatal beating
media:group.media:description:
While protesters in the United States mourn George Floyd, police brutality is also a concern south of the border in Mexico. Mexicans protested against police brutality in the second-largest city, Guadalajara, accusing the police officers who arrested a construction worker of beating him to death. The government's human rights minister has condemned the use of excessive force. But police deny that. Al Jazeera's Laura Burdon-Manley has more.

entry.title: Turkey cracks down as cybercrime rises amid pandemic

media:group.media:title: Turkey cracks down as cybercrime rises amid pandemic
media:group.media:description:

In Turkey, the police cybercrime unit has seen an enormous increase in the number of phishing sites, designed to steal users' financial information. Al Jazeera's Sinem Koseoglu reports from Istanbul.

media:group.media:title: Libyan government 'retakes' Haftar stronghold Tarhuna
media:group.media:description:
Libya's Deputy Defence minister says government troops have taken control of Tarhuna. That is the last stronghold of renegade military commander Khalifa Haftar in northwest Libya - about 65 kilometres from the capital, Tripoli. On Thursday, the UN-recognised government announced that it had regained full control of Tripoli. Haftar's forces still hold large swaths of territory in the east and south of the country.

entry.title: Nicaragua gov't accused of ‘ignoring' COVID-19 pandemic

media:group.media:title: Nicaragua gov't accused of ‘ignoring' COVID-19 pandemic
media:group.media:description:
As nations around the world locked down this spring to help contain the coronavirus, Nicaragua's president assured his country there was nothing to worry about. Schools and businesses remained open as Daniel Ortega encouraged residents to attend concerts, parades and sporting events. Doctors in the country say the situation is now out of control. Al Jazeera's Teresa Bo reports.

entry.title: World Environment Day sees calls for protection post-COVID-19

media:group.media:title: World Environment Day sees calls for protection post-COVID-19
media:group.media:description:

On World Environment Day there are calls for greater efforts to protect the planet’s living systems - from the largest land mammal on Earth to the trillions of microbes in the ocean that help create the air we breathe. Al Jazeera's Nick Clark reports.

entry.title: US Navy veteran released by Iran arrives in Switzerland

media:group.media:title: US Navy veteran released by Iran arrives in Switzerland

entry.title: Thailand aims to revive tourism amid pandemic

media:group.media:title: Thailand aims to revive tourism amid pandemic
media:group.media:description:
Thailand’s capital Bangkok was named the world’s most visited city in 2019. With 40 million visitors - tourism is referred to as the engine driving the kingdom’s economy. But with global travel halted during the pandemic, that engine is running on empty. Al Jazeera's Scott Heidler looks at the Thai government's plan to bring tourists back to Thailand’s cities and beaches.

entry.title: Ahmaud Arbery: Suspects in US murder case to face trial

media:group.media:title: Ahmaud Arbery: Suspects in US murder case to face trial
media:group.media:description:
A judge in the US state of Georgia has ruled that three men charged with the murder of a Black man will go on trial. Ahmaud Arbery was chased and shot several times by a retired white police officer and his son in February. But they were only charged in May after a video of the shooting in Brunswick led to nationwide protests. Al Jazeera's Andy Gallacher reports.
